Autorregressive models

In an autoregression model, the variable of interest is forecast using a linear combination of past values of the variable. The term autoregression indicates that it is a regression of the variable against itself.

These models are based on the idea that crrent values of the series depend on previous values of the same series.

An autoregressive model of order p \(AR(p)\) has the form:

\[\begin{align*} y_{t} = c + \phi_{1}y_{t-1} + \phi_{2}y_{t-2} + \dots + \phi_{p}y_{t-p} + \varepsilon_{t} \end{align*}\]
  • \(\varepsilon_t\) is white noise
  • \(y_{t}\) is stationary

Shifting terms to the left and using backshift notation, we may express these model as:

\[ y_t - \phi_1 y_{t-1} - \phi_2 y_{t-2} - \dots+ \phi_p y_{t-p} = c + \varepsilon_t \]

\[ (1-\phi_1\,B-\phi_2\,B^2-\dots-\phi_p\,B^p)y_t = c + \varepsilon_t \]

\[ \left(1-\sum_{i=1}^p\phi_iB^i\right)y_t = c+ \varepsilon_t \]

We will now further simplify the notation definint the autoregressive operator:

\[ \phi(B)=1-\phi_1\,B-\phi_2\,B^2-\dots-\phi_p\,B^p = \left(1-\sum_{i=1}^p\phi_iB^i\right) \]

The model might be simply expressed as:

\[ \phi(B)y_t=c+ \varepsilon_t \]

Stationarity conditions of AR(p) models. Restrictions on the coefficients

Note that the model is a regression of random components. The predictors (the lagged values of \(y_t\)) are random, whereas in normal regression we assumed that the predictors were not random variables. This will give rise to some technical difficulties, most notably the need to impose some restrictions on the parameters of the autoregressive model, whereas no restrictions applied in normal regression.

These conditions are focused on ensuring the resulting models represent stationary data. Mathematically, they translate into ensuring that the complex roots of the following polynomial lie outside the unit circle of the complex plane. For the specific math behind is, the reader is referred to chapter 4 of reference [2] and chapter 3 of reference [3].

\[ 1 - \phi_1z-\phi_2z^2-\dots-\phi_pz^p \]

Here we give the constraints for \(AR(1)\) (p=1) and \(AR(2)\) (p=2) models:

  • For an \(AR(1)\) model: \(-1 < \phi_1 < 1\).
  • For an \(AR(2)\) model, we already have three constraints:
    • \(-1 < \phi_2 < 1\)
    • \(\phi_1+\phi_2 < 1\)
    • \(\phi_2-\phi_1 < 1\)
  • For an \(AR(3)\), the restrictions get more complex.

When using statistical packages such as fable, the software already takes care of the matter.

Example AR(1) model:

The equation for an AR(1) model is:

\[\begin{align*} y_{t} = c + \phi_{1}y_{t-1} + \varepsilon_{t} \end{align*}\]
  • when \(\phi_1 = 1\) and \(c = 0\), the restrictions on the parameters are not satisfied and we end up with a random walk model, which is not stationary.
  • when \(\phi_1 = 1\) and \(c \neq 0\) the restrictions on the parameters are not satisfied and we end up with a random walk with drift model, which is not stationary.
  • when \(\phi_1 = 0\) and \(c = 0\), the model is equivalent to white noise.
  • when \(\phi_1 < 0\), \(y_t\) tends to oscillate around the mean. If, additionally, \(c=0\) then the model tends to oscillate between positive and negative values.

AR(1) vs AR(2) examples:

Autoregressive models are very flexible for handling a wide range of time series patterns, and in an ARIMA context they are restricted to handle only stationary series. Below some examples on the aspect of autoregressive models that satisfy the parameter restrictions:

  • In both cases \(\varepsilon_t \sim N(0, 1)\). Changing the variance of this term will only change the variance of the series, not the patterns.

  • Changing the \(\phi_k\) parameters (within their constraints) generates different time series patterns.

  • AR(1) in figure has equation \(y_t = 18 - 0.8y_{t-1} + \varepsilon_t\)

  • AR(2) in figure has equation \(y_t = 8 + 1.3y_{t-1} - 0.7y_{t-2} + \varepsilon_t\)

Moving Average models

Consider a white noise series \(\varepsilon_t\) and think of \(\varepsilon_t\) as a âshockâ to the process at time \(t\). A moving average model considers the forecast variable as a regression on that shock and its past values:

\[\begin{align*} y_{t} = c + \varepsilon_t + \theta_{1}\varepsilon_{t-1} + \theta_{2}\varepsilon_{t-2} + \dots + \theta_{q}\varepsilon_{t-q}, \end{align*}\]

The name moving average is used because \(y_t\) can be though as a weighted moving average of the past few âshocksâ, although the coefficients of the regression rarely add up to one, as they would in a moving average. Do not confuse moving average models with the moving average smoothing discussed in time series decomposition.

A case of particular interest is to consider the shocks \(\varepsilon_t\) as forecast errors. That is, to predict \(y_t\) as a regression on previous forecast errors. Since independence does not hold in general for time series, this is a good way of modelling possible relationships between the errors of the latest few forecast values. Of course, we do not observe the values of \(\varepsilon_t\), so it is not really a regression in the usual sense.

Unlike the autoregressive process, the moving average process is stationary for any value of the parameters. Below some examples of Moving Average processes:

  • In both cases \(\varepsilon_t \sim N(0, 1)\). Changing the variance of this term will only change the variance of the series, not the patterns.

  • Changing the \(\theta_k\) parameters (within their constraints) generates different time series patterns.

  • MA(1): \(y_t = 20 + \varepsilon_t + 0.8\varepsilon_{t-1}\)

  • MA(2): \(y_t = \varepsilon_t - \varepsilon_{t-1} + 0.8\varepsilon_{t-2}\)

Causality and autoregressive models - Autoregressive related to MA.

Stationary \(AR(p)\) models can be written as an \(MA(\infty)\) model. That is, we can find an expression for the \(y_t\) of the \(AR(p)\) model in terms of an infinite sum on \(\varepsilon_t\) and its past values. We will show later that this is actually important in an ARIMA context.

As an example, an \(AR(1)\) model could be written as an \(MA(\infty)\) model as follows simply using recursive substitution:

\[\begin{align*} y_t &= \phi_1y_{t-1} + \varepsilon_t\\ &= \phi_1(\phi_1y_{t-2} + \varepsilon_{t-1}) + \varepsilon_t\\ &= \phi_1^2y_{t-2} + \phi_1 \varepsilon_{t-1} + \varepsilon_t\\ &= \phi_1^3y_{t-3} + \phi_1^2\varepsilon_{t-2} + \phi_1 \varepsilon_{t-1} + \varepsilon_t\\ &\text{etc.} \end{align*}\]

If the constraint \(-1 < \phi_1 < 1\) is satisfied, the value \(\phi_{1}^k\) decreases as \(k\) increases. Hence extending the recursion to infinity the weight associated to the lag of \(y_t\) would tend to 0 and we would reach the desired \(MA(\infty)\) process:

\[\begin{align*} y_t = \varepsilon_t + \phi_1 \varepsilon_{t-1} + \phi_1^2 \varepsilon_{t-2} + \phi_1^3 \varepsilon_{t-3} + \cdots = MA(\infty) \end{align*}\]

Note that the above was possible thanks to the constraint \(-1 < \phi_1 < 1\).

The term âcausalityâ is used to signal that for such a model \(y_t\) depends only on the current shock \(\varepsilon_t\) and its past values

Invertibility and Moving Average Models

If certain constraints are imposed on the MA parameters then we can ensure that the model is invertible, i.e.Â the \(MA(q)\) process can be expressed as an \(AR(\infty)\) process. In other words: we can obtain an expression for \(\varepsilon_t\) as a regression of infinite terms of \(y_t\) and its lags.

These invertibility constraints are similar to the stationary constraints for \(AR(p)\) processes and are obtained by setting the coefficients \(\theta, \theta_1,...\theta_q\) such that the complex roots of the following equation lie outside the unit circle of the complex plane:

\[ 1 - \theta_1z-\theta_2z^2-\dots-\theta_qz^q \] The mathematical justification for this is complex and not in the scope of this course. The reader interested is referred to [2] and [3].

Here we give the conditions corresponding to the first values of \(q\):

  • For an \(MA(1)\) model: \(-1<\theta_1<1\)
  • For an \(MA(2)\) model:
    • \(-1<\theta_1<1\)
    • \(\theta_2+\theta_1 >-1\)
    • \(\theta_1 -\theta_2 < 1\)
  • For \(q \geq 3\) the constraints get more complex, but they will be handled automatically by the fable package or other estimation software

Some properties of invertible models

Invertible models have mathematical properties that make them desirable for forecasting uses.

As an example, let us consider the MA(1) model and try to give an interpretation of the significance of the invertibility conditions for this model. The MA(1) model has the form:

\[ y_t = c + \varepsilon_t + \theta_1 \varepsilon_{t-1} \] Re-arranging to obtain an expression for \(\varepsilon_t\) and substituting recursively, we obtain:

\[\begin{align*} \varepsilon_t &= y_t - c - \theta_1\varepsilon_{t-1} \\ &= y_t - c - \theta_1(y_{t-1} - c - \theta_1\varepsilon_{t-2}) \\ &= (y_t-\theta_1y_{t-1})-c(1+\theta_1)-\theta_1^2\varepsilon_{t-2} \\ &= \dots \\ &= (y_t-\theta_1y_{t-1}-\theta_1^2y_{t-2})-c(1+\theta_1+\theta_1^2)- \theta_1\varepsilon_{t-3} \\ &\text{etc.} \end{align*}\]

The \(\dots\) in the equations above correspond to substituting \(\varepsilon_{t-2}\) by \(y_{t-2} - c - \theta_1\varepsilon_{t-3}\) expanding and grouping.

Extending the recursion to infinity we would reach the following expression for \(\varepsilon_t\):

\[\begin{align*} \varepsilon_t = \sum_{j=0}^\infty (-\theta_1)^j y_{t-j}-c\sum_{j=0}^\infty (-\theta_1)^j \tag{*} \end{align*}\]

The equation for the unit-roots of the model had led us to the following constraints for the values of _1 for an MA(1) model:

\[ -1<\theta_1<1 \] Looking at equation \(*\) we see indeed that this is the only thing that makes sense.

  • If \(|\theta_1|>1\)
    • The weights associated to each \(y_{t-j}\) would increase as the lags increased. That is: distant observations would have the same effect on the current errors as recent observations. This does not make much sense from a forecasting perspective.
    • The geometric progression multiplying the constant \(c\) would not have a convergent sum.
  • If \(|\theta_1|=1\)
    • The weights would be the same for every \(y_{t-j}\), so distant observations would have the same effect on the current errors as recent observations. This does not make much sense from a forecasting perspective.
    • The geometric progression multiplying the constant \(c\) would not have a convergent sum.
  • If \(|\theta_1|<1 \rightarrow -1<\theta_1<1\)
    • More recent observations have a higher weight than observations in the distant past. Thus the process is invertible only in this situation.
    • The geometric progression multiplying the constant \(c\) converges.

ARMA(p, q) models

Combining \(AR(p)\) and \(MA(q)\) processes we can produce \(ARMA(p,q)\) processes. These are very flexible for handling stationary time series.

\[\begin{equation} y_{t} = c + \phi_{1}y_{t-1} + \cdots + \phi_{p}y_{t-p} + \theta_{1}\varepsilon_{t-1} + \cdots + \theta_{q}\varepsilon_{t-q} + \varepsilon_{t} \end{equation}\]

When we start combining models in this manner, it is useful to use the backshift notation:

\[\begin{equation} \tag{9.2} \begin{array}{c c c c} (1-\phi_1B - \cdots - \phi_p B^p)y_t = &c + (1 + \theta_1 B + \cdots + \theta_q B^q)\varepsilon_t\\ {\uparrow} & {\uparrow}\\ \text{AR($p$)} & \text{MA($q$)}\\ \end{array} \end{equation}\]

ARMA Models and stationary processes:

These statements are proved in references [2] and [3].

  • Mathematically, Woldâs decomposition theorem shows that any stationary time series may be represented as a linear combination of white noise.
  • On the other hand it can be shown that any ARMA model can be expressed in a form that is a linear combination of white noise, provided the stationarity and invertibility constraints on the parameters are satisfied.

As a consequence, ARMA models are capable of modelling stationary time series. It may not always be the best model, but models of this form are viable in many situations and indeed are very wide-spread through the industry for these reasons.

Order selection for ARMA(p,q) processes:

Selecting appropriate values for \(p\) and \(q\) can be difficult. We will use two approaches:

  1. Inspecting the Autocorrelation (ACF) and Partial Autocorrelation (PACF) diagrams of the stationary process. This will let us infer appropriate values for \(p\) and \(q\) and later try a few more models around these values

  2. Using the automatic search in the ARIMA() function from the fable() package, which looks for values of \(p\) and \(q\) does this automatically. However this approach has its own caveats, as we will explore.

It is important to have both approaches clear, because simply using ARIMA() and letting it chose the model for you can in many instances lead to overparametrized models.

ACF

Measures the relationship between \(y_t\) and its lags \(y_{t-k}\). Potential masking of relationships:

  • If \(y_t\) and \(y_{t-1}\) are correlated, \(y_{t-1}\) and \(y_{t-2}\) are also correlated
  • \(y_t\) and \(y_{t-2}\) might be correlated simply because they are both connected yo \(y_{t-1}\) rather than due to information contained in \(y_{t-2}\) that could be useful to forecast \(y_t\).

PACF - Partial Autocorrelation Function

Many times we want to find the correlation between two variables but removing the effect of other variables. This is known as partial autocorrelation.

In the case of a time series \({y_t}\), it corresponds to finding the autocorrelation between variables \((y_t, y_{t-k})\) while removing the effect of all the lags in-between them: \(y_{t-1}, t_{t-2},\dots , y_{t-k+1}\).

In more general but simplified terms, if we had three variables \(x\), \(y\) and \(z\), the partial autocorrelation between \(x\) and \(y\) would be the correlation between \(x\) and \(y\) having removed any effect derived from the fact that both \(x\) and \(y\) might be correlated to \(z\). We write this function as:

\[ \rho_{xy|z}=corr\{x-\hat x, y-\hat y\} \]

where we imply that we want to find the correlation between \(x\) and \(y\) while removing the effect of \(z\).

There is an easy interpretation of partial autocorrelation in terms of the coefficients of a linear regression model. Think of the following two models:

\[ y_t = \beta_0 + \beta_1z \]

\[ y_t = \beta_0+\beta_1x+\beta_2z \]

In the first model, \(\beta_1\) can be interpreted as the linear dependency between y and z. In the second model, \(\beta_2\) would be interpreted as the linear dependency between \(y\) and \(z\) with the linear dependency between \(x\) and \(y\) already accounted for.

In the case of time series, we could fit an autoregression model (a regression of the series \(y_t\) on its lagged values) and perform a similar interpretation. Consider the following two models:

\[ y_t = \beta_0 + \phi_1y_{t-3} \]

\[ y_t = \beta_0+\phi_1y_{t-1}+\phi_2y_{t-2}+\phi_3y_{t-3} \]

In the first model, \(\phi_1\) can be interpreted as the linear dependency between \(y\) and \(y_{t-3}\). In the second model, \(\phi_3\) would be interpreted as the linear dependency between \(y\) and \(y_{t-3}\) with the linear dependency between \(y\) and \(y_{t-1}\) and \(y_{t-2}\) already accounted for.

Following this line of reasoning, it is clear that the first autocorrelation coefficient is equal to the first partial autocorrelation coefficient, because there are no lags in between \(y_t\) and \(y_{t-1}\).

In the example above, one possible algorithm to obtain the value of \(\phi_3\) would be the following:

  1. Fit the model \(\hat{y_t} = ay_{t-1}+by_{t-2}\)
  2. Fit the model \(\hat{y_{t-3}} = cy_{t-1}+dy_{t-2}\)
  3. Compute the residuals of the model fitted in step 1: \(y_t - \hat{y_t}\)
  4. Compute the residuals of the model fitted in step 2: \(y_{t-3} - \hat{y_{t-3}}\)
  5. Compute the correlation coefficient between the residuals of step 3 and the residuals of step 4.

Basically we are correlating \(y_t\) and \(y_{t-3}\) having removed their linear dependency with \(y_{t-1}\) and \(y_{t-2}\).

In practice there are more efficient algorithms for computing the partial autocorrelations than fitting all of these autoregressions, but they all lead to the same results.

Lets compute the PACF for the egyptian exports using the function PACF

ACF and PACF of AR(p), MA(q) and ARMA(p, q) models

ACF and PACF plots - relation with \(p\) and \(q\)

This section summarizes the way to assess the ACF and PACF plots to manually select values for the orders \(p\) and \(q\) of the model.

To fully understand it, the examples that follow this section are essential, as well as the additional examples that will be provided for students to assess.

Once the data has been made stationary, we want to compute the ACF and PACF function because they may assist us in determining the orders p and q for the model.

The plots must be generated for the stationary data, since it is this data that can be modeled using an ARMA process.

When inspecting the plots, the following table (ref 2. and 3.) can be used to determine the orders:

AR(p) (q=0) MA(q) (p=0) ARMA(p,q)
ACF Tails-off Cuts off after lag q Tails-off
PACF Cuts-off after lag p Tails off Tails-off

In this table:

  • tails-off means that the function is exponentially decaying or sinusoidally decaying.
  • cuts-off means that there are no relevant autocorrelation coefficients beyond lag p (if we are dealing with the AR case) or q (if we are dealing with the MA case).

Case where both cut-off: it can be shown that for an ARMA process this is not possible. However for real data there are situations where this might seem the case. We will see an example of this at the end of the chapter.

Case where both tail-off: in the case where both p and q are positive (ARMA model), then the ACF and PACF will both tail-off and the diagrams are not very helpful in identifying the order of either \(p\) or \(q\). In this case we may follow two approaches:

  1. Resort directly to an automated search with ARIMA() to do the model search for us.
  2. Start with \(p=q=1\) following a parsimony principle. From this initial model we would change orders as necessary taking into account:
  • Residuals plots
  • Significance of the coefficients of the model
  • information criteria

In other words, we would perform the manual search ourselves.

All this is better understood through examples.

Important note: keep in mind that in ARIMA models, the information criteria can be compared only among models with the same order of differencing. This will be later explained, but it is important that you keep this in mind. The reason is that differencing changes the data to which the ARMA model is fitted (it removed the trend and the seasonality!).

Examples of ACF and PACF functions of simulated data:

I am going going to use the function sarima.sim from an additional library, astsa (associated to references [2] and [3]). This functions enables us to quickly simulate AR and MA processes. That is: we are going to define a data generating process and create a sample of artificial data that will follow that process (just like when we extract 100 samples from a normal distribution to create white noise).

We are then going depict the ACFs and PACFs of these samples and see if the patterns match what we would expect in order to recognize the values of \(p\) and \(q\) if we were to manually fit the model.

Finally we are going to see if the automated function ARIMA(), from the package fable, is capable of detecting the underlying data generating process from the data.

AR(1) simulation example

Let us simulate a model \(AR(1)\) with parameter \(\phi=0.75\):

set.seed(1011)
y_ar1 <- sarima.sim(ar=c(0.75)) %>% as_tsibble()
y_ar1 %>% autoplot()
Plot variable not specified, automatically selected `.vars = value`

Now we can depict the ACF and PACF. Either sepparately or using gg_tsdisplay():

y_ar1 %>% ACF() %>% autoplot()
Response variable not specified, automatically selected `var = value`

y_ar1 %>% PACF() %>% autoplot()
Response variable not specified, automatically selected `var = value`

y_ar1 %>% gg_tsdisplay(value, plot_type="partial")

Going back to our table we see that the PACF clearly cuts off after lag 1, as expected from an AR(1) model. The ACF on the other hand decays in a sinusoidal manner.

In this case the pattern is very recognizable due to:

  1. The fact that this is a pure AR() model that we have simulated and not real data
  2. The values of the parameters.

Real data may be a bit more difficult to spot due to its inherent noise.

Let us see if the ARIMA function is capable of detecting the actual data generating process:

y_ar1 %>% model(ARIMA()) %>% report()
Model not specified, defaulting to automatic modelling of the `value` variable.
Override this using the model formula.

      0.8028

In this case, the function ARIMA() successfully detects the true data generating process.

AR(2) simulation example

Let us simulate a model \(AR(2)\) with parameter \(\phi_1=0.75\) and \(\phi_2 = -0.8\):

set.seed(1011)
y_ar2 <- sarima.sim(ar=c(0.75, -0.8)) %>% as_tsibble()
y_ar2 %>% autoplot()
Plot variable not specified, automatically selected `.vars = value`

y_ar2 %>% ACF() %>% autoplot()
Response variable not specified, automatically selected `var = value`

y_ar2 %>% PACF() %>% autoplot()
Response variable not specified, automatically selected `var = value`

y_ar2 %>% gg_tsdisplay(value, plot_type="partial")

This time PACF cuts-off at lag 2, as expected from an AR2 model. ACF tails off, but its does so in a different manner (still sinusoidal though) than before.

Let us see if the ARIMA() function now recognizes the underlying model:

y_ar2 %>% model(ARIMA()) %>% report()
Model not specified, defaulting to automatic modelling of the `value` variable.
Override this using the model formula.
Series: value 
Model: ARIMA(2,0,1) 

Coefficients:
         ar1      ar2     ma1
      0.7143  -0.7184  0.1002
s.e.  0.0409   0.0336  0.0576

sigma^2 estimated as 1.045:  log likelihood=-719.99
AIC=1447.98   AICc=1448.06   BIC=1464.84

As we can see, the ARIMA() function returns an over-parametrized model that includes an additional autoregressive term as well as even a moving average termâ¦

This means that the automated approach fails to recognise the true data generating process. However, in a forecasting context, where we do not actually know the true data generating process, this model might be good enough. We should judge its performance as usual using, for example, cross-validation.

Remark: AIC vs BIC discussion

Let us compare the AIC of this automatically fitted model with the performance of a model fitted using the actual value of the parameters:

y_ar2 %>% model(
            manual = ARIMA(value ~ pdq(2,0,0)),
            auto_arima = ARIMA(),
            auto_arima_bic = ARIMA(ic="bic")
          ) %>% glance()
Model not specified, defaulting to automatic modelling of the `value` variable. Override this using the model formula.
Model not specified, defaulting to automatic modelling of the `value` variable. Override this using the model formula.
# A tibble: 3 Ã 8
  .model         sigma2 log_lik   AIC  AICc   BIC ar_roots  ma_roots 
  <chr>           <dbl>   <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <list>    <list>   
1 manual           1.05   -721. 1449. 1449. 1462. <cpl [2]> <cpl [0]>
2 auto_arima       1.05   -720. 1448. 1448. 1465. <cpl [2]> <cpl [1]>
3 auto_arima_bic   1.05   -721. 1449. 1449. 1462. <cpl [2]> <cpl [0]>
  • Note that the auto_arima model is best than the manual model in terms of AICc and AIC! Remember however that AICc is not focused on looking for the true data generating process

However note that the BIC of the model following the true data generating process has better BIC!. This is because given enough data, BIC has a feature that, if there is a true underlyting model, it will select it.

Thenâ¦ why not always use BIC? Because:

  1. There is rarely if ever a true underlying model.
  2. Even if there is a model, selecting it will not necessarily give the best forecasts. This is because the parameter estimates may not be accurate (remember we need to estimate the values of all the \(\phi_i\) and \(\theta_i\) from the data).

MA(2) model

Lets try \(\theta_1=0.65\) and \(\theta_2=0.85\):

set.seed(1011)
y_ma2 <- sarima.sim(ma=c(0.65, 0.25)) %>% as_tsibble()
y_ma2 %>% autoplot()
Plot variable not specified, automatically selected `.vars = value`

Extreme case: overparametrized white-noise

This case is here only to prove the potential risks associated to automatic forecasting techniques:

set.seed(666)
y_norm <- rnorm(1000) %>% as_tibble() %>% mutate(index=row_number()) %>% as_tsibble(index=index)

y_norm %>% model(ARIMA()) %>% report()
Model not specified, defaulting to automatic modelling of the `value` variable.
Override this using the model formula.
Series: value 
Model: ARIMA(2,0,1) 

Coefficients:
          ar1      ar2     ma1
      -0.9744  -0.0477  0.9509
s.e.   0.0429   0.0321  0.0294

sigma^2 estimated as 0.9657:  log likelihood=-1400
AIC=2808.01   AICc=2808.05   BIC=2827.64
y_norm %>% gg_tsdisplay(value, plot_type="partial")

Here we can see how it is a good idea to at least check the ACF and PACF prior to blindly fitting ARIMA() to our data. Again auto-ARIMA has failed to recognize the true underlying model. This is the reason it is an equally beloved and criticised function.

It is always a good idea to check the ACF and PACF. The underlying model might be blatantly obvious. Do not be lazy.

Example Egyptian Exports

eg_exports <- global_economy %>%
  filter(Code == "EGY")

eg_exports  %>%
  autoplot(Exports) +
  labs(y = "% of GDP", title = "Egyptian exports")

eg_exports %>% gg_tsdisplay(Exports, plot_type="partial")

Example - Central African Republic Exports

global_economy %>%
  filter(Code == "CAF") %>%
  autoplot(Exports) +
  labs(title="Central African Republic exports",
       y="% of GDP")

  1. The time plot shows some non-stationarity, with an overall decline. The improvement in 1994 was due to a new government which overthrew the military junta and had some initial success, before unrest caused further economic decline.

  2. There is no evidence of changing variance, so we will not do a Box-Cox transformation.

  3. To address the non-stationarity, we will take a first difference of the data. The differenced data are shown below:

global_economy %>%
  filter(Code == "CAF") %>%
  gg_tsdisplay(difference(Exports), plot_type='partial')
Warning: Removed 1 row(s) containing missing values (geom_path).
Warning: Removed 1 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

These now appear to be stationary.

Step 4. Plot ACF and PACF. In this case both seem to be cutting-off. In this situations we will fit two manual models:

  • Model 1: assuming PACF cut-off and ACF tail-off: AR(2) model
  • Model 2: assuming ACF cut-off and PACF tail-off: MA(3) model

Step 5. We plot these models along with two automatically fitted models

caf_fit <- global_economy %>%
  filter(Code == "CAF") %>%
  model(arima210 = ARIMA(Exports ~ pdq(2,1,0)),
        arima013 = ARIMA(Exports ~ pdq(0,1,3)),
        stepwise = ARIMA(Exports),
        search = ARIMA(Exports, stepwise=FALSE))
caf_fit %>% pivot_longer(!Country, names_to = "Model name",
                         values_to = "Orders")

Step 7. Produce forecasts from the chosen model:

caf_fit %>%
  forecast(h=5) %>%
  filter(.model=='search') %>%
  autoplot(global_economy)

In this case:

  • The extra work to include AR and MA term has made little difference to the point forecasts from those compared with a NAIVE model (we compare with a NAIVE because we have non-seasonal data)

  • The prediction intervals of the ARIMA model are much narrower (feel free to check). Note however that prediction intervals are based on the assumption the data is determined by the autoregression on its past values and the moving average filter of the errors. But as you know in such macroeconomic data external events may have a much greater impact on this.
